CAPE TOWN - A Malmesbury resident who was at Liebenberg Primary School when a swarm of bees attacked the crowd, while the school’s athletics day was under way, said it was like watching a “horror movie”.Ten learners from St Thomas Primary School were stung by a swarm of bees during the athletics day hosted by Liebenberg Primary School on Friday morning.Two learners had to get medical treatment in hospital, and were released later that day.Sherna Vermeulen who was at the school to watch the athletics, said chaos erupted after one of the learners threw a stone into a bee hive that was in an old tree on the premises.“It was like watching a horror movie. The bees were attacking people, who ran to get away from them.“There were a few people who got hurt in the process, after falling on the ground. The fire brigade and ambulance were contacted and they arrived very fast,” said Vermeulen.The Western Cape government’s emergency medical services (EMS), said a call for assistance came through to the West Coast Emergency Communication Centre at 10.39am.A rescue vehicle and three ambulances were dispatched immediately.“Ten patients were stung by a swarm of bees that flew over the crowd, while the school’s athletics day was under way.“Two of the 10 patients were transported to Swartland and Malmesbury hospitals. The patients sustained minor injuries,” EMS spokesperson Deanna February said.Western Cape education department spokesperson Bronagh Hammond said all learners were treated, and the bees soon dispersed. Cape Times